post_text: Not only is it Super Hero day in the elementary, but these kiddos became a Super Squad! We read a very fitting book this morning called Super Kena. Super Kena is about a little girl who is teased about having hearing aids. She decides that she is going to gather her group of friends who all have super powers like her (asthma, diabetes, allergies, glasses, a stutter etc.). They became a Super Squad of heroes and showed off their Super Powers! Our kiddos made masks and letters to show off their Super Powers as an Adams Central Super Squad! Happy Homecoming week from the Super Squad!

post_text: 2020 Graduate and current Adams Central FFA member Ashlyn Mohling has been selected as one of 4 National FFA proficiency finalists in the area of Equine Entrepreneurship. post_text: Adams Central Seniors Chance Mignery and Caitlin Tibbs recently competed in the Nebraska High School Finals Rodeo, where they both finished in the top 4 of all competitors in their respective events, earning them the opportunity to represent the state of Nebraska at the National High School Rodeo Finals July 19th-25th in Guthrie, Oklahoma. Caitlin Tibbs qualified in Pole Bending, and Chance Mignery qualified in the Boys Cutting Contest, after winning the short go performance on the final day of competition. Congratulations and good luck!!
text: Adams Central Seniors Chance Mignery and Caitlin Tibbs recently competed in the Nebraska High School Finals Rodeo, where they both finished in the top 4 of all competitors in their respective events, earning them the opportunity to represent the state of Nebraska at the National High School Rodeo Finals July 19th-25th in Guthrie, Oklahoma. Caitlin Tibbs qualified in Pole Bending, and Chance Mignery qualified in the Boys Cutting Contest, after winning the short go performance on the final day of competition. Congratulations and good luck!!

In Nebraska, 8th-graders and 10-12th-graders don't need new physicals for the 2020-21 school year athletics if the school has one on file from this past school year (according to NSAA provisions). However, you may still have your student get a physical, and if that's the case, please send a copy to the AC High School office so we have the most recent copy on file. (you can bring or send a copy to school or email it to karen.allen@adams-central.org)
7th graders and incoming freshmen need a new physical this year.

It's finally here!!
The last days of school/check-in are next week! You've received your scheduled time. Please be prompt and things should run efficiently and safely for all. If you haven't been around the AC Campus recently, Adams Central Avenue is now closed from the Hiway 6 intersection to our roundabout. You will have to come to the schools from the north AND everyone will need to park at the Elementary.
7-11th grade students on Wednesday & Thursday will need to plan ahead and allow time to walk over. They will need to enter the building through the junior high wing doors.
**Please note** There is a lot of construction going on, so pay extra attention as there is a lot of equipment coming in and out of the high school lot.
Thank you for your understanding and for all you're doing to help your student succeed!
See you next week! ‚ù§Ô∏èüíô

Once again, another important Adams Central annual event upon us that we are unable to have.
Tomorrow, Thursday, May 7, we were supposed to hold Honors Night, which is a special night to honor the seniors, National Honor Society members and Adams Central staff.
We will post the list of senior award and scholarship winners tomorrow at 7 p.m. here, and it will also be on the school website, adamscentral.us
There's a great group of students that are being honored for their achievements and we can't wait to share it with all of you!

The Adams Central art students have had a tremendous year producing artworks that have won many awards at various shows. Even though the Art Expo had to be canceled for this year, you can still view all of the artworks by the talented Adams Central students at the Artsonia Online Gallery. Use the link below to enjoy a virtual Art Expo.

https://www.artsonia.com/schools/school.asp?id=10102

Although the senior art students could not showcase their four years of art accomplishments at the Art Expo, the class created a fun lip dub video to celebrate their graduation.

https://youtu.be/3E5i0ueYoAM

If your student's artwork is not visible on Artsonia contact crystal.hassenstab@adams-central.org to find out how to grant permission.

Congratulations to Adams Central's FBLA members who earned awards at the State Leadership Conference recently. The contest was a virtual conference. These members had taken tests or completed projects before Covid 19 restrictions began. These students would have qualified for the national competition in Salt Lake City in June, but that conference will now also be virtual.

~Kieren Feeney - State Champion in Electronic Career Portfolio
~Kyara Fike, Savannah Harper, Ethan Rogers - State Runner-up in Sports Entertainment and Management
~Sadie Carpenter, Drake Vorderstrasse,
Melinda Nienhueser - State Runner-up in Entrepreneurship
~Drake Vorderstrasse - 5th Place Public Service Announcement
~Jersie Frerichs, Savannah Harper - 8th Place Emerging Business Issues

post_text:
Check out this comment from Omaha World Herald Sports Writer Mike Patterson:

‚ÄúGood sports

While Lincoln Christian was the official winner of the Class C-1 sportsmanship award, an honorable mention must go to Adams Central.

After losing the 10:45 a.m. semifinal Friday against North Bend, the Adams Central players were still in the arena later for the Class B semifinal between Beatrice and Scottsbluff. Seeing the Scottsbluff student section dwarfed by the large Beatrice student contingent, the Patriots players joined the Bearcats‚Äô group and cheered as if it was their own school playing.

That‚Äôs my definition of good sports.‚Äù

That‚Äôs what it‚Äôs all about, folks.

post_text: AC 5th-grade students will be learning about raising trout for the Nebraska Games and Parks this semester. After the trout hatch and grow in a controlled environment, the 5th graders will take a trip to one of Nebraska's freshwater fish release areas and release the trout they have studied and raised. Students will also learn about the Nebraska Game and Parks fish and wildlife conservation projects within our state.

post_text: Students in Mrs. Kliewer's Anatomy & Physiology participated in a CyberSurgeon Mission. During their mission, students became part of an emergency medical team on a National Institutes of Health mercy ship traveling up the Amazon River. Students interacted with a "Chief Medical Officer" at the Challenger Learning Center to diagnose and treat a variety of medical conditions.

post_text:
Congrats to the following 8th grade students for having their artworks selected to the Scholastic Art Awards Show! Out of the over 3,000 artworks submitted state-wide only about a third of the artworks are selected for the show. The selected artworks are then judged as Gold Key, Silver Key and Honorable Mention.

Hannah Gengenbach received Gold Key for her mixed media artwork "Mother Nature's Sorrows", Silver Key for her painting "Bathtub Bonding", and Honorable Mention for pen and ink self portrait. Kaylee Buchholz received Gold Key for her giraffe painting "Savanna Spots". Kori Curtis received Silver Key for her painting "Eyes of Determination". Megyn Scott received Silver Key for her flower painting "A Kiss from the Sun". Hannah Himmelberg received Honorable Mention for her flower painting "Aloha". And Macey Russell received Honorable Mention for her sunset painting "Broken Sunset".

post_text: The Adams Central National Honor Society Canned Food Drive was successful. A total of 9,095 items was donated by students and staff from the Adams Central School District. post_text: At today's Holiday Band Concert, former director Tom Jaworski came back and conducted the band for a song. After, he was gifted with a quilt made out of old band uniforms from his days teaching at Adams Central. It was great to see him again, and we hope he enjoys the quilt! If you are interested in purchasing a quilt, please contact the high school and ask for Jodi. (402-463-3285). Thank you Phyllis O'Dey for your time and talent.

post_text: This picture is from one of Mrs. Portenier's Culinary Arts classes. Yesterday she switched up their lab groups (they were not in their comfort zone with their friends. She threw a couple difficult recipes at them that we had not even gone over and needed to practice for an event. To her surprise not a single one of them rolled their eyes, squaked back, or complained. Not. A. Single. One. The opposite. They got right to work! They worked hard even though they may not have been comfortable in a new group or new station. Seems like a small thing but it's really not. It's how she can tell they are ready to graduate. Surely we adults can even relate to having to work with people who we aren't comfortable with!
